He notices that the function $f(x)$ satisfies the mean value theorem on the interval $[a, b]$. This theorem states that there exists at least one number $c$ in the interval $(a, b)$ such that 

\begin{equation}
f'(c) = \frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a}
\end{equation}

The blogger also knows that the function $f(x)$ satisfies the conditions of the Rolle's theorem, which is a special case of the mean value theorem and states that if $f(a) = f(b)$, then there exists at least one number $c$ in the interval $(a, b)$ such that $f'(c) = 0$.

If the function $f(x)$ satisfies both the mean value theorem and the Rolle's theorem on the interval $[a, b]$, what can we infer about the function $f(x)$ on this interval? Provide a proof for your answer.
